The paper deals with a problem of designing a non-adaptive quantitative group testing algorithm, which involves coding theory, information theory, and graph theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely category. The paper also proposes a sparse graph code-based algorithm, which involves graph theory and coding theory, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) likely categories. The paper also involves theoretical analysis and simulation results, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible category. Finally, the paper deals with a combinatorial optimization problem, making cs.CC (Computational Complexity) a possible category.
